While it has been known for many years that corticosteroid use benefits boys with Duchenne Muscular dystrophy (DMD), most clinicians do not consider treating until after age 3 or 4 years of age.

 The primary reason for the delay is that daily corticosteroid use has many side effects including short stature, obesity, and osteoporosis.

 A recent randomized blinded study of weekend oral corticosteroid use over one year showed equal improvement in strength with fewer side effects, particularly as related to growth and cushingoid changes.

 The investigators will test the efficacy of oral weekend corticosteroid use in infants and young boys with DMD who are under age 30 months.

